[30;1m339 | [0m[35museful to calculate the SZA in relation to the true solar time. True solar time relates to the[0m
[30;1m340 | [0m[35mposition of the sun with respect to the observer, which is different depending on the exact[0m
[30;1m341 | [0m[35mlongitude. For example, two hours before the sun crosses the meridian (the highest point it would[0m
[30;1m342 | [0m[35mreach that day) corresponds to a true solar time of 10 a.m. The SZA has a strong dependence on the[0m
[30;1m343 | [0m[35mobserver's latitude. For example, at a latitude of 50 degrees N at the start of January, the[0m
[30;1m344 | [0m[35mnoontime SZA is 73.0 but a different observer at 20 degrees N would measure the noontime SZA to be[0m

[30;1m2371 | [0m[35m    How to use units notation[0m
[30;1m2372 | [0m[35m    -------------------------[0m
[30;1m2373 | [0m[35m    The **Great Tables** units notation involves a shorthand of writing units that feels familiar[0m
